 primarily from various U.S. federal
 foreign
 and state tax audit developments during the year.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Our 2011 effective tax rate included net tax costs of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$52 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;
 primarily due to&amp;#160;various U.S. federal and state tax audit developments during the year as well as the revaluation of state deferred tax assets and liabilities resulting from state tax legislation enacted in 2011.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Our unrecognized tax benefits of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$259 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; at December&amp;#160;28
 2013 are included in other current liabilities and other liabilities. If we had recognized all of these benefits
 the net impact on our income tax provision would have been &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$168 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;. The amount of net unrecognized tax benefits could decrease by approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$50 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$75 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; during the next 12 months. We include accrued interest and penalties related to uncertain tax positions in our tax provision. We have accrued interest and penalties of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$74 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; as of December&amp;#160;28
 2013 and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$67 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; as of December 29
 2012. rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We have entered into a tax sharing agreement with Mondel&amp;#275;z International
 which provides that for periods prior to October&amp;#160;1
 2012
 Mondel&amp;#275;z International is liable for and will indemnify us against all U.S. federal income taxes and substantially all foreign income taxes
 excluding Canadian income taxes; and that we are liable for and will indemnify Mondel&amp;#275;z International against U.S. state income taxes and Canadian federal and provincial income taxes.&amp;#160;However
 if we breach certain covenants or other obligations or are involved in certain change-in-control transactions
 Mondel&amp;#275;z International may not be required to indemnify us for income taxes arising pursuant to the Spin-Off. Similarly
 if Mondel&amp;#275;z International breaches certain covenants or other obligations or are involved in other change-in-control transactions
 we may not be required to indemnify them for income taxes arising pursuant to the Spin-Off.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Our U.S. operations were included in Mondel&amp;#275;z International&amp;#8217;s U.S. federal consolidated income tax returns for tax periods through October&amp;#160;1
 2012.&amp;#160;In July 2012
 Mondel&amp;#275;z International reached a final resolution on a U.S. federal income tax audit of the 2004-2006 tax years and on a Canadian income tax audit of certain matters related to the 2003-2006 tax years.&amp;#160;The U.S. federal statute of limitations remains open for tax year 2007 and forward
 and federal income tax returns for 2007-2009 are currently under examination.&amp;#160;As noted above Kraft is indemnified for federal taxes U.S. state and local and foreign jurisdictions have statutes of limitations generally ranging from three to five years unless we agree to an extension.&amp;#160;In Canada
 our only significant foreign jurisdiction
 the earliest open tax year is 2006.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;At December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 Kraft had outside tax basis in excess of book basis in certain foreign subsidiaries in which earnings are indefinitely reinvested.  As of that date
 applicable U.S. federal income taxes and foreign withholding taxes had not been provided on approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;&gt;$375 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of unremitted earnings of such foreign subsidiaries.&amp;#160; If such earnings were to be remitted
 our incremental tax cost would be approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$15 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;The tax effects of temporary differences that gave rise to deferred income tax assets and liabilities consisted of the following at December 28
 2013 and December&amp;#160;29

 operating loss carryforwards
 and tax credit carryforwards.&amp;#160; Inherent in determining our annual tax rate are judgments regarding business plans
 planning opportunities and expectations about future outcomes. Realization of certain deferred tax assets
 primarily net operating loss and other carryforwards
 is dependent upon generating sufficient taxable income in the appropriate jurisdiction prior to the expiration of the carryforward periods. &amp;#160;See Note 12

 the Financial Accounting Standards Board issued an accounting standard update which will require us to present an unrecognized tax benefit as a reduction to a deferred tax asset for a net operating loss carryforward
 a similar tax loss
 or a tax credit carryforward in our financial statements
 with certain exceptions.  The update will be effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15

 as follows:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=padding-top:12px;font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=width:47px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:top rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;padding-left:23px;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;#8226;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:top; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Pension benefits &amp;#8211; We provide pension coverage to certain U.S. and non-U.S. employees through separate plans. Local statutory requirements govern many of these plans. Salaried and non-union hourly employees hired prior to 2009 in the U.S. and 2011 in Canada are eligible to participate in our pension plans. We will freeze U.S. pension plans for U.S. salaried and non-union hourly employees who are currently earning pension benefits as of December 31
 2019 and non-U.S. pension plans for non-U.S. salaried and non-union hourly employees who are currently earning pension benefits as of December 31
 2023. We will calculate the pension benefits using the continuing pay and service through December 31
 2019 for the U.S. plans and December 31

 and their cost is charged to expense over the working life of the covered employees.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-left:4px;padding-top:12px;text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold;&gt;Pension Plans&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;&gt;Obligations and Funded Status:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;The projected benefit obligations

rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We remeasure all of our postemployment benefit plans at least annually at the end of our fiscal year.  The remeasurement as of December 28
 2013
 resulted in an aggregate benefit from market-based impacts of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$1.3 billion&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; primarily driven by an 80 basis point weighted average increase in the discount rate and excess asset returns. We recorded &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$707 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of the benefit from market-based impacts in cost of sales and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$561 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in selling
 general and administrative expenses. The annual remeasurement resulted in benefit from market-based impacts of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$29 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; as of December 29
 2012 and an expense from market-based impacts of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$68 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; as of December 31
 2011.  Market-based impacts are included in actuarial (gains) / losses and in settlements in the table above. We disclose market-based impacts separately in order to provide better transparency of our operating results.  We define market-based impacts as the costs or benefits resulting from the change in discount rates
 the difference between our estimated and actual return on trust assets
 and other assumption changes driven by changes in the law or other external factors.&amp;#160; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Net pension costs included settlement losses of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$69 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2013 related to retiring employees who elected lump-sum payments. Net pension costs also included special termination benefits associated with our voluntary early retirement program of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$62 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2013
 which were included in our Restructuring Program.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We determine the expected return on plan assets based on asset fair values as of the measurement date.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;As of December 28
 2013
 we expected to amortize an estimated &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$5 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of prior service cost from accumulated other comprehensive earnings / (losses) into net periodic pension cost for the combined U.S. and non-U.S. pension plans during 2014.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We used the following weighted average assumptions to determine our net pension cost for the years ended December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December 31
 2011:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;div style=padding-left:0px;text-indent:0px;line-height:normal;padding-top:10px;&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td colspan=18 rowspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td width=22% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=11% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=11% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=12% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=11% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=11% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=11% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px;padding-right:2px;  fixed-income debt instruments with durations that match the expected future cash flows of the benefit obligations. We determine our expected rate of return on plan assets from the plan assets&amp;#8217; historical long-term investment performance
 current and future asset allocation
 and estimates of future long-term returns by asset class.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;&gt;Plan Assets:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;The fair value of pension plan assets at December&amp;#160;28

 2012 from the above table related to certain insurance contracts as they are reported at contract value

 as reported by the managers of the trusts and as supported by the unit prices of actual purchase and sale transactions. Level 2 plan assets also include corporate bonds and other fixed-income securities
 valued using independent observable market inputs
 such as matrix pricing
 yield curves
 and indices.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=width:47px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:top rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;padding-left:23px;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;#8226;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:top; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Level 3 &amp;#8211; includes primarily real estate valued using unobservable inputs that reflect the plans&amp;#8217; assumptions that market participants would use in pricing the assets
 based on the best information available. Fair value estimates for real estate investments are calculated by the investment managers using the present value of future cash flows expected to be received from the investments
 based on valuation methodologies such as appraisals
 local market conditions
 and current and projected operating performance.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Changes in our Level 3 plan assets

rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=overflow:hidden;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:right;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;100&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff;padding-right:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;background-color:#cceeff;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px;padding-right:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=overflow:hidden;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:right;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;100&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff;padding-right:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;background-color:#cceeff;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px;padding-right:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=overflow:hidden;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:right;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;100&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff;padding-right:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;During 2013
 we began a new liability-driven investment strategy for pension assets.  This strategy
 which will be phased in over the next several years
 better aligns our pension assets with the projected benefit obligation to reduce volatility by targeting an investment of approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;80%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of our U.S. plan assets in fixed-income securities and approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;20%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in equity securities.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;As of December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;43%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of our U.S. plan assets are in fixed-income securities and approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;53%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; are in equity securities. The strategy uses actively managed and indexed U.S. investment grade fixed-income securities (which constitute &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;97%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; or more of fixed-income securities) with lesser allocations to high yield fixed-income securities
 indexed U.S. equity securities
 and actively managed and indexed international equity securities.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;For the plans outside the U.S.
 the investment strategy is subject to local regulations and the asset / liability profiles of the plans in each individual country. In aggregate
 the long-term asset allocation targets of our non-U.S. plans are broadly characterized as a mix of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;70%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; fixed-income securities and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;30%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; equity securities. The other asset balance of our non-U.S. plans at December&amp;#160;28
 2013 primarily related to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$8 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in cash accounts.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We attempt to maintain our target asset allocation by rebalancing between asset classes as we make contributions and monthly benefit payments.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;&gt;Employer Contributions:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;In order to align cash flows with expenses and reduce volatility
 we have executed a level funding strategy. For our U.S. qualified pension plans
 in 2014
 we currently are only required to make a nominal cash contribution under the Pension Protection Act of 2006. However
 based on our level funding strategy
 we estimate that 2014 pension contributions will be approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$160 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; to our U.S. plans and approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$40 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; to our non-U.S. plans.  Our actual contributions may be different due to many factors
 including changes in tax and other benefit laws
 significant differences between expected and actual pension asset performance or interest rates
 or other factors. In 2013
 we contributed &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$435 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; to our U.S. pension plans and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$176 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; to our non-U.S. pension plans. Of the total 2013 pension contributions
 approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$518 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; was voluntary. We make contributions to our U.S. and non-U.S. pension plans
 primarily
 to the extent that they are tax deductible. In addition
 employees contributed &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$5 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2013 to our non-U.S. plans and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$3 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2012.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;&gt;Future Benefit Payments:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;The estimated future benefit payments from our pension plans at December&amp;#160;28
 2013 were:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;div style=padding-left:0px;text-indent:0px;line-height:normal;padding-top:10px;&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td colspan=9 rowspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td width=66% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=14% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=14% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px;padding-right:2px; These plans provide pension benefits to retirees under certain collective bargaining agreements. We also sponsor and contribute to employee savings plans. These plans cover eligible salaried
 non-union
 and union employees. Our contributions and costs are determined by the matching of employee contributions
 as defined by the plans. Amounts charged to expense for defined contribution plans totaled &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$61 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2013 and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$12 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2012 subsequent to the Spin-Off.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold;&gt;Postretirement Benefit Plans&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;&gt;Obligations:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Our postretirement health care plans are not funded. Our expected health care cost trend rate is based on historical costs.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Assumed health care cost trend rates have a significant impact on the amounts reported for the health care plans.  we recorded a benefit from market-based impacts of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$292 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; as of December 28
 2013
 primarily driven by an 80 basis point weighted average increase in the discount rate. We recorded expense from market-based impacts of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$250 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; as of December 29
 2012.  Market-based impacts are included in actuarial (gains) / losses in the table above. The special termination benefits were associated with our voluntary early retirement program in 2013. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;As of December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 we expected to amortize an estimated &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$29 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of prior service credit from accumulated other comprehensive earnings / (losses) into net postretirement health care costs during 2014.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We used the following weighted average assumptions to determine our net postretirement cost for the years ended December&amp;#160;28
 2013

rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:right;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;42&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;A benefit from market-based impacts of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$1 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; as of December 28
 2013 and an expense of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$2 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; as of December 29
 2012 and December 31
 2011 were included in actuarial (gains) / losses in the table above.  Other postemployment costs in 2011 primarily relate to the recognition of the partially funded Canadian postemployment plan.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;As of December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 we do not expect to amortize any prior service cost / (credit) for the other postemployment benefit plans from accumulated other comprehensive earnings / (losses) into net postemployment costs during 2014.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold;&gt;Our Participation in Mondel&amp;#275;z International&amp;#8217;s Pension and Other Postemployment Benefit Plans and the Spin-Off Impact&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Prior to the Spin-off
 Mondel&amp;#275;z International provided defined benefit pension
 postretirement health care
 defined contribution
 and multiemployer pension and medical benefits to our eligible employees and retirees. As such
 we applied the multiemployer plan accounting approach and these liabilities were not reflected in our consolidated balance sheets. We provided pension coverage for certain employees of our Canadian operations through separate plans and certain pension and postemployment benefits of our Canadian operations
 which were included in our financial statements prior to the Spin-Off. As part of the Spin-Off
 the plans were split and we assumed the obligations previously provided by Mondel&amp;#275;z International. Accordingly
 Mondel&amp;#275;z International transferred to us the plan assets and liabilities associated with our active
 retired
 and other former employees
 including liabilities for most of the retired North American Mondel&amp;#275;z International employees. We assumed net benefit plan liabilities of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$5.5 billion&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; from Mondel&amp;#275;z International
 which was in addition to the &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$0.1 billion&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of net benefit plan liabilities we had previously reported in our historical financial statements
 for a total liability of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$5.6 billion&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; on October&amp;#160;1
 2012.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:10px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Total Mondel&amp;#275;z International benefit plan costs allocated to us were &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$491 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in the first nine months of 2012 prior to the Spin-Off and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$497 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2011. The expense allocations for these benefits were determined based on a review of personnel by business unit and based on allocations of corporate or other shared functional personnel. These allocated costs are reflected in our cost of sales and selling


 postretirement health care
 defined contribution
 and multiemployer pension and medical benefits. Our pension
 postretirement
 and other postemployment (collectively
 &amp;#8220;postemployment&amp;#8221;) benefit plans cover most salaried and certain hourly employees. The cost of these plans is charged to expense over the working life of the covered employees. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;In December of 2012
 we elected to change our method of accounting for defined benefit costs to a mark-to-market policy. Under this accounting method
 we recognize net actuarial gains or losses and changes in the fair value of plan assets in cost of sales and selling
 general and administrative expenses immediately upon remeasurement
 which is at least annually.  This change has been reported through retrospective application of the policy to all periods presented.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Prior to the Spin-Off

  
  
  
  
  
  

 we record expense related to certain consumer incentive programs as a reduction of net revenues.  Previously
 we included this expense in selling
 general and administrative expenses.  We have revised prior periods to reflect this in our current presentation.  The impacts of these revisions
 which were not material to any prior period
 reduced net revenues and selling
 general and administrative expenses by &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$68 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2012 and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$79 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2011.  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;During 2013
 we determined that we had overstated indefinite-lived tradenames in the purchase accounting of a 2001 acquisition.  Therefore
 we have revised our financial statements to reduce our Foodservice indefinite-lived intangible assets by &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$403 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;
 reduce our deferred tax liability by &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$150 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;
 and increase goodwill by &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$253 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;. This misstatement was not material to any of our prior period financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;In 2012
 we misclassified approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$879 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of United States Foodservice long-lived assets as being located in Canada.  We have corrected and revised the balances reported in our long-lived assets by geographic area table in Note 15
 &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;&gt;Segment Reporting&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;
 as of December 29

 2013 and December&amp;#160;29

 plant and equipment
 net&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px;background-color:#cceeff; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:right;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;4
115&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;background-color:#cceeff;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px;padding-right:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=overflow:hidden;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px;background-color:#cceeff; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:right;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;4
204&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;border-bottom:3px double #000000;background-color:#cceeff; rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;div style=text-align:left;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;In 2013

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

 plant and equipment are stated at historical cost and depreciated by the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets. Machinery and equipment are depreciated over periods ranging from &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;3&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;20 years&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; and buildings and improvements over periods up to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;40 years&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;. Capitalized software costs are included in property
 plant and equipment and amortized on a straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives of the software
 which do not exceed &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;7 years&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We review long-lived assets for impairment when conditions exist that indicate the carrying amount of the assets may not be fully recoverable. Such conditions include significant adverse changes in the business climate
 current-period operating or cash flow losses
 significant declines in forecasted operations
 or a current expectation that an asset group will be disposed of before the end of its useful life.  We perform undiscounted operating cash flow analyses to determine if an impairment exists. When testing for impairment of assets held for use
 we group assets and liabilities at the lowest level for which cash flows are separately identifiable. If an impairment is determined to exist
 the loss is calculated based on estimated fair value. Impairment losses on assets to be disposed of
 if any
 are based on the estimated proceeds to be received


 plant and equipment at December 28
 2013 and December&amp;#160;29

 asset disposals
 and other activities that do not qualify for special accounting treatment as exit or disposal activities.&amp;#160; Included within cost saving initiatives are activities related to the previously disclosed multi-year &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;&gt;$650 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; restructuring program approved by Kraft&amp;#8217;s Board of Directors on October 29
 2012 (the &amp;#8220;Restructuring Program&amp;#8221;).  We have reduced our estimate of the total Restructuring Program costs to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$625 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;br clear=none/&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;&gt;Restructuring Program:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Our Restructuring Program consists of approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$270 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of restructuring costs
 approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$285 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of implementation costs
 and approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$70 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; of Spin-Off transition costs. We expect approximately one-half of these costs will be cash expenditures. Restructuring costs reflect primarily severance
 asset disposals
 a voluntary early retirement program and other manufacturing-related costs. Implementation costs are directly attributable to the  Restructuring Program; however
 they do not qualify for special accounting treatment as exit or disposal activities. These costs primarily relate to reorganization costs related to our sales function
 the information systems infrastructure
 and accelerated depreciation on assets. Spin-Off transition costs have not been allocated to the segments because they consist mostly of professional service fees within the finance
 legal
 and information systems functions.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;As of December 28
 2013
 we have incurred Restructuring Program costs of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$585 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; since the inception of the Restructuring Program.  We have spent &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;$261 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in cash. We expect to complete the Restructuring Program by the end of 2014.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We recorded Restructuring Program costs and spending in the consolidated financial statements as follows:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;div style=padding-left:0px;text-indent:0px;line-height:normal;padding-top:10px;&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td colspan=8 rowspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td width=73% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=11% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=11% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td width=1% rowspan=1 colspan=1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=vertical-align:bottom;padding-left:2px;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:2px;padding-right:2px;  including refrigerated meals
 refreshment beverages
 coffee
 cheese
 and other grocery products
 primarily in the United States and Canada. Effective July 1
 2013
 we began managing and reporting operating results through &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;&gt;six&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; reportable segments: Beverages
 Cheese
&amp;#160;Refrigerated Meals
 Meals &amp;amp; Desserts
 Enhancers &amp;amp; Snack Nuts
 and Canada.  Our remaining businesses
 including our Foodservice and Exports businesses
 are aggregated and disclosed as &amp;#8220;Other Businesses&amp;#8221;.  We reflect this reorganization for all the historical periods presented.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Management uses segment operating income to evaluate segment performance and allocate resources. We believe it is appropriate to disclose this measure to help investors analyze segment performance and trends. Segment operating income excludes unrealized gains and losses on hedging activities
 certain components of our postemployment benefit plans
 and general corporate expenses (which are a component of selling
 general and administrative expenses) for all periods presented. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We exclude the unrealized gains and losses on hedging activities (which are a component of cost of sales) from segment operating income in order to provide better transparency of our segment operating results. Once realized
 the gains and losses on hedging activities are recorded within segment operating results. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We exclude certain components of our postemployment benefit plans (which are a component of cost of sales and selling
 general and administrative expenses) from segment operating income because we centrally manage postemployment benefit plan funding decisions and the determination of discount rate
 expected rate of return on plan assets
 and other actuarial assumptions. We also manage market-based impacts to these benefit plans centrally. Therefore
 we allocate only the service cost component of our pension plan expense to segment operating income.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;Furthermore
 we centrally manage interest and other expense
 net. Accordingly
 we do not present these items by segment because they are excluded from the segment profitability measure that management reviews.  We use the same accounting policies for the segments as those described in Note 1

 2013
 we were involved in 60 active proceedings in the United States under the Comprehensive Environmental Response
 Compensation and Liability Act (and other similar state actions and legislation) related to our current operations and certain closed
 inactive or divested operations for which we retain liability. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;As of December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 we had accrued an amount we deemed appropriate for environmental remediation. Based on information currently available
 we believe that the ultimate resolution of existing environmental remediation actions and our compliance in general with environmental laws and regulations will not have a material effect on our financial condition or results from operations. However

  
  
  
  
  
  
  

 including workers' compensation
 general liability
 automobile liability

 consumer incentives
 and trade promotions. Consumer incentives and trade promotions include
 but are not limited to
 discounts
 coupons
 rebates
 in-store display incentives
 and volume-based incentives. Consumer incentive and trade promotion activities are recorded as a reduction to revenues based on amounts estimated as being due to customers and consumers at the end of a period. We base these estimates principally on historical utilization and redemption rates. For interim reporting purposes
 we charge advertising and consumer incentive expenses to operations as a percentage of volume
 based on estimated volume and related expense for the full year.  We review and adjust these estimates each quarter based on actual experience and other information.  We do not defer these costs on our year-end consolidated balance sheet and all marketing costs are recorded as an expense in the year incurred. Advertising expense was &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$747 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2013
 &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$640 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2012
 and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;$535 million&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt; in 2011. We record marketing expense in selling
 general and administrative expense
 except for consumer incentives and trade promotions
 which are recorded in net revenues. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=font-family:Arial;font-size:10pt;&gt;We expense costs as incurred for product research and development.
